© University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name, toponymic from Winkhill (Lincs), or perhaps topographic from an unattested Middle English * <i>winkel</i>, derived from Old English * <i>wincel</i> ‘nook, corner, bend in a river’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":34,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Wyncoll was born in 1421, his father, John Wyncoll, was 61 and his mother, Alice Dover, was 31. He had at least 2 sons with Thomasine Page. He died on 1 July 1459, at the age of 38, and was buried in Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1421–01 Jul 1459":"1421–1. juuli 1459","1421–1459":"1421–1459","1428–1467":"1428–1467","1440–1519":"1440–1519","1455–1521":"1455–1521","1360–1421":"1360–1421","1390–1424":"1390–1424","1459":"1459","1424":"1424","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","1421":"1421","01 Jul 1459":"1. juuli 1459","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1519":"1519","1390":"1390","1428":"1428","Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England":"Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St Lawrence Churchyard, Little Waldingfield, Babergh District, Suffolk, England":"Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1421–01 Jul 1459":"1421–1. heinäkuuta 1459","1421–1459":"1421–1459","1428–1467":"1428–1467","1440–1519":"1440–1519","1455–1521":"1455–1521","1360–1421":"1360–1421","1390–1424":"1390–1424","1459":"1459","1424":"1424","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","1421":"1421","01 Jul 1459":"1. heinäkuuta 1459","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1519":"1519","1390":"1390","1428":"1428","Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England":"Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","St Lawrence Churchyard, Little Waldingfield, Babergh District, Suffolk, England":"Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1421–01 Jul 1459":"1421–1 juillet 1459","1421–1459":"1421–1459","1428–1467":"1428–1467","1440–1519":"1440–1519","1455–1521":"1455–1521","1360–1421":"1360–1421","1390–1424":"1390–1424","1459":"1459","1424":"1424","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","1421":"1421","01 Jul 1459":"1 juillet 1459","1440":"1440","1360":"1360","1519":"1519","1390":"1390","1428":"1428","Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England":"Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, Angleterre","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","St Lawrence Churchyard, Little Waldingfield, Babergh District, Suffolk, England":"Little Waldingfield, Suff